 areas. The authors provide new data and reflections on these linguistic communities which have languages somewhere in between the majority and minority, and re-evaluate the opposition between ‘majority’ and ‘minority’. The book focuses on seven European cities, providing detailed information on their current situation and on the corresponding evolution of their linguistic repertoire. The book aims to improve our understanding of how and why languages live and decay, and of how intercultural cities, where communities show interest in each other’s culture and language, can be better developed and encouraged.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aLanguage and languagesxVariation. 0aLanguage policyxSocial aspects. 0aLinguistic geographyxVariation. 0aMultilingualismxSocial aspects. 0aSociolinguistics. 0aUrban dialectsxSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh  aIntercultural cities.  aLanguage policies.  aLinguistic Repertoires.  aLocal and global languages.  aMajority and minority languages.  aMedium-sized Linguistic Communities.  aMultilingualism.  aUrban Areas.1 aBoix-Fuster, Emili, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoix-Fuster, Emili, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aExtra, Guus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGonzález Pascual, Iago, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHambye, Philippe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHernández Dobon, Francesc Jesús, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJørgensen, J. Normann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaegaard, Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNicolás Amorós, 